# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: innings-pitched
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The **1902 major league baseball season** was contested from April 17 through October 5, 1902.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American League (AL), with the Philadelphia Athletics winning the AL pennant.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant for the second consecutive season.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Milwaukee Brewers moved and became the St.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns; the franchise would remain in St.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis through 1953, and in 1954 moved again to become the modern Baltimore Orioles.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This season would be the last of this season's Baltimore Orioles, who would fold following the conclusion of the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues renamed as the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The 1902 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with every team playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 19, with a one-off game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Americans, with the rest of the season beginning April 23.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 29, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (8 in AL, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Across both leagues, Sammy Strang tied as a leader in runs at 109 (108 with the Chicago White Stockings of the AL and 1 with the Chicago Orphans of the NL).
[src:innings-pitched/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds leave League Park (where they played for 18 seasons) and move to the Palace of the Fans, where they would go on to play for ten seasons through 1911.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:innings-pitched/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The **1904 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 to October 10, 1904.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans and New York Giants finished atop the standings for the American League and National League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason: with still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues, the Giants declined to meet the Americans in the 1904 World Series.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the Americans were the defending World Series from the 1903 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns and Detroit Tigers played 11 consecutive games against each other in September—the first six in Detroit and the final five in St.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis—the most games played consecutively between two teams in major league history.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings shortened their name to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The 1904 schedule consisted of 154 games (an increase from 140 from the previous season) for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 140-game, 20-games-each format that had been in place from the 1901 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League would see their final day of the regular season on October 9 & 10, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the New York Highlanders, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] 29 tie games (18 in AL, 11 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the New York Giants refused to play against the Boston Americans or any other team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators leave American League Park (where they played three seasons) and move into a new American League Park, where they would go on to play seven seasons through 1910.
[src:innings-pitched/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Highlanders play one game at Wiedenmeyer's Park in Newark, New Jersey on Sunday, July 17, as a makeup between them and the Detroit Tigers and to avoid New York City's blue laws.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The **1908 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1908.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 8, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the prior year's postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the fifth modern World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to one, capturing their second championship in franchise history, and the first team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans renamed as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The 1908 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 14.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games (10 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1908 World Series in five games.
[src:innings-pitched/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their final game at Columbia Park with a doubleheader on October 3 against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Shibe Park for the start of the 1909 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The **1912 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1912.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the New York Giants and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the ninth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 8 on October 16.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Giants, four games to three (with one tie), capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1903.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1911 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] During the season, *Harper's Weekly* conducted a detailed accounting of the expenses of major league clubs, reaching a figure of approximately $175,000 to $200,000.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Rustlers renamed as the Boston Braves.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 11, featured all sixteen teams, only the second time every team has started their season on the same day (first being two years prior with the 1910 season).
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 16.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (8 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 16 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the New York Giants in the 1912 World Series in seven games.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw two teams play their last seasons at their respective venues.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw three teams play in new venues.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, was renamed to Robison Field by Helene Britton, named after her father and uncle, Frank and Stanley Robison, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1912-major-league-baseball-season] To accommodate for large crowds, the New York Highlanders would play three home games at the Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants, on May 30 and a doubleheader on September 2.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The **1915 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1915.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League regular season ended on October 3, and saw the Chicago Whales winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season for the National League and American League ended on October 7, with the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 12th World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 13.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Phillies, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1912.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Braves from the 1914 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series had again featured the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, though this time with their opposite-league counterparts.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers relocated to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Buffeds, Chicago Federals, and Cleveland Naps renamed as the Buffalo Blues, Chicago Whales, and Cleveland Indians, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League brought an antitrust lawsuit against the National and American Leagues prior to the 1915 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The parties eventually reached a settlement and the Federal League disbanded after the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The 1915 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 10, featuring all eight teams.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, featuring the 16 teams of those two leagues, as had been scheduled the season prior.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 3.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season for the National and American Leagues was October 7.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 13.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National League established that player-managers would count against the player limit, so the bench manager would be unable to insert himself in any game during the season without forfeiting the right to carry one of the players on his roster.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The penalty for violating the rule was forfeiture of the game.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (10 in AL, 13 in NL, 8 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series in five games.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Indianapolis Hoosiers from Indianapolis, Indiana to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers, they leave Federal League Park and move into Harrison Park.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves would play their last game at Fenway Park on July 26, having shared the park with the Boston Red Sox since the middle of 1914, and opened Braves Field on August 18, playing their final 26 of 78 home games and where they would go on to play for 38 seasons through 1952.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs would play their final game at West Side Park on October 3 against the St.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the home of the Chicago Whales (who would fold before the 1916 season), Weeghman Park for the start of the 1916 season.
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] For games 3 and 4 of the World Series, the Boston Red Sox use the Boston Braves home of Braves Field due to its larger capacity over their home at Fenway Park (40,000 to 27,000).
[src:innings-pitched/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first year in a row where a World Series winning Red Sox used Braves Field.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] In baseball, the statistic **innings pitched** (**IP**) is the number of innings a pitcher has completed, measured by the number of batters and baserunners that have been put out while the pitcher is on the pitching mound in a game.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] Three outs made is equal to one inning pitched.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] One out counts as one-third of an inning, and two outs as two-thirds of an inning.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] Sometimes, the statistic is written 34.1, 72.2, or 91.0, for example, to represent 34+1⁄3 innings, 72+2⁄3 innings, and 91 innings exactly, respectively.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] Runners left on base by a pitcher are not counted in determining innings pitched.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] It is possible for a pitcher to enter a game, give up several hits and possibly even several runs, and be removed before achieving any outs, thereby recording a total of zero innings pitched.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] Alternatively, it is possible for a pitcher to enter a situation where there are two runners on base and no outs.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] He could throw one pitch that results in a triple play, and for that one pitch, he would be credited with a full-inning pitched.
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] In Major League Baseball, the only active players in the top 100 all-time at the end of the 2009 season were Tom Glavine (ranked 30th with 4,413+1⁄3 IP), Randy Johnson (ranked 38th with 4,135+1⁄3), Jamie Moyer (ranked 45th with 3,908+2⁄3) and John Smoltz (ranked 74th with 3473).
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] By the end of the 2018 season, only two active players were in the top 100 all-time: CC Sabathia (ranked 73rd with 3470), and Bartolo Colón (ranked 74th with 3461+2⁄3).
[src:innings-pitched/innings-pitched] This is because over time, innings pitched have declined.
